<doc id="1184376" wikidata="Q4860582" url="?curid=1184376" title="Bargmann's limit">
<text>In quantum mechanics, Bargmann&#x27;s limit, named for Valentine Bargmann, provides an upper bound on the number formula_1 of bound states with azimuthal quantum number formula_2 in a system with central potential formula_3. It takes the form

:formula_4

This limit is the best possible upper bound in such a way that for a given formula_2, one can always construct a potential formula_6 for which formula_1 is arbitrarily close to this upper bound. Note that the Dirac delta function potential attains this limit. After the first proof of this inequality by Valentine Bargmann in 1953, Julian Schwinger presented an alternative way of deriving it in 1961.

== Rigorous formulation and proof ==
Stated in a formal mathematical way, Bargmann&#x27;s limit goes as follows. Let formula_8 be a spherically symmetric potential, such that it is piecewise continuous in formula_9, formula_10 for formula_11 and formula_12 for formula_13, where formula_14 and formula_15. If

:formula_16

then the number of bound states formula_1 with azimuthal quantum number formula_2 for a particle of mass formula_19 obeying the corresponding Schrödinger equation, is bounded from above by

:formula_20

Although the original proof by Valentine Bargmann is quite technical, the main idea follows from two general theorems on ordinary differential equations, the Sturm Oscillation Theorem and the Sturm-Picone Comparison Theorem. If we denote by formula_21 the wave function subject to the given potential with total energy formula_22 and azimuthal quantum number formula_2, the Sturm Oscillation Theorem implies that formula_1 equals the number of nodes of formula_21. From the Sturm-Picone Comparison Theorem, it follows that when subject to a stronger potential formula_26 (i.e. formula_27 for all formula_28), the number of nodes either grows or remains the same. Thus, more specifically, we can replace the potential formula_3 by formula_30. For the corresponding wave function with total energy formula_22 and azimuthal quantum number formula_2, denoted by formula_33, the radial Schrödinger equation becomes

:formula_34

with formula_35. By applying variation of parameters, one can obtain the following implicit solution

:formula_36

where formula_37 is given by

:formula_38

If we now denote all successive nodes of formula_33 by formula_40, one can show from the implicit solution above that for consecutive nodes formula_41 and formula_42

:formula_43

From this, we can conclude that

:formula_44

proving Bargmann&#x27;s limit. Note that as the integral on the right is assumed to be finite, so must be formula_45 and formula_1. Furthermore, for a given value of formula_2, one can always construct a potential formula_6 for which formula_1 is arbitrarily close to Bargmann&#x27;s limit. The idea to obtain such a potential, is to approximate Dirac delta function potentials, as these attain the limit exactly. An example of such a construction can be found in Bargmann&#x27;s original paper.

